{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512438"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:55:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:55:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11896"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11896"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.06,0.07,0.05,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108236"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4493"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11896"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90648"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1330"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1693"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2737"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47377"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108236"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of central crushing chest pain. He has a medical history of ischaemic heart disease and metabolic syndrome. He takes aspirin, metformin, and atorvastatin. The pain is not relieved by glyceryl trinitrate spray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. ECG and troponins support the diagnosis of a lateral wall ST-elevation myocardial infarction. He undergoes immediate primary percutaneous coronary intervention and is admitted to the Coronary Care Unit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFive days after admission, he develops sudden onset dyspnoea, severe hypotension, and cardiogenic shock, requiring Intensive Care admission. Clinical examination reveals bibasal crepitations and a new pan-systolic murmur with an absent first heart sound. Arterial blood gas shows type 1 respiratory failure. A transoesophageal echocardiogram is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Papillary muscle rupture","Left ventricle aneurysm","Cor pulmonale","Left atrial thrombus","Aortic stenosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of papillary muscle rupture: acute deterioration 5 days post-myocardial infarction with sudden onset dyspnoea, hypotension, and a new pan-systolic murmur. \u003Cstrong\u003EPapillary muscle rupture\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious mechanical complication of myocardial infarction, occurring in 1-5% of cases, typically 2-7 days after the initial event. The postero-medial papillary muscle is more commonly affected due to its single blood supply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft ventricle aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E is another mechanical complication of myocardial infarction but typically presents more gradually with heart failure symptoms and would not cause an acute pan-systolic murmur. It usually develops weeks to months after the initial event.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECor pulmonale\u003C/strong\u003E refers to right heart failure secondary to lung disease. While it can present with right-sided heart failure signs, it would not explain the acute deterioration or the new pan-systolic murmur in this post-MI setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft atrial thrombus\u003C/strong\u003E can form in patients with poor left atrial function but would not explain the acute mitral regurgitation or cardiogenic shock. It typically presents with systemic embolisation rather than acute heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E produces an ejection systolic murmur rather than a pan-systolic murmur and would have been present on admission. It would not explain the acute deterioration in this timeline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of papillary muscle rupture requires immediate surgical intervention due to its high mortality rate (approaching 50% even with surgery). Medical stabilisation with afterload reduction and inotropic support serves only as a bridge to definitive surgical treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Papillary muscle rupture typically occurs 2-7 days after myocardial infarction and presents with acute pulmonary oedema and cardiogenic shock.","A new pan-systolic murmur with absent S1 in the post-MI period strongly suggests acute mitral regurgitation.","Immediate surgical intervention is required for papillary muscle rupture due to its high mortality rate."],"references":["Mueed A, Khatti S, Ashraf J, et al. Arrhythmia in Acute Myocardial Infarction: A Six-Month Retrospective Analysis From the National Institute of Cardiovascular Diseases. Cureus. 2020;12(11):e11322. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33304665/","McQuillan, Brendan \u0026 Weyman, A. (2000). Severe mitral regurgitation secondary to partial papillary muscle rupture following myocardial infarction. Reviews in cardiovascular medicine. 2000;1:57-60. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12457152/","Colombo, M.G., Kirchberger, I., Amann, U. et al. Association between admission anemia and long-term mortality in patients with acute myocardial infarction: results from the MONICA/KORA myocardial infarction registry. BMC Cardiovasc Disord . 2018. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5845173/","French JK, Hellkamp AS, Armstrong PW, et al. Mechanical complications after percutaneous coronary intervention in ST-elevation myocardial infarction (from APEX-AMI).Am J Cardiol. 2010;105:59\u201363. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20102891/","Bhardwaj B, Sidhu G, Balla S, et al. Outcomes and hospital utilization in patients with papillary muscle rupture associated with acute myocardial infarction.Am J Cardiol. 2020; 125:1020\u20131025. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31973809/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90648"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11896"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17017"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17017"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f46c0c58-11f9-43ac-a6a3-76172390cd8a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f46c0c58-11f9-43ac-a6a3-76172390cd8a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":850,"height":594}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90648"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T19:06:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-